{"parse":{"title":"Salva congruitate","pageid":25948756,"revid":577107704,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Salva congruitate</b></i><sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Latin\" title=\"Latin\">Latin</a> scholastic term in <a href=\"/wiki/Logic\" title=\"Logic\">logic</a>, which means \"without becoming ill-formed\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> <i><a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/salvus\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikt:salvus\">salva</a></i> meaning <i>rescue</i>, <i>salvation</i>, <i>welfare</i> and <i><a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/congruo\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikt:congruo\">congruitate</a></i> meaning <i>combine</i>, <i>coincide</i>, <i>agree</i>. Salva Congruitate is used in logic to mean that two terms may be <a href=\"/wiki/Substitution_(logic)\" title=\"Substitution (logic)\">substituted</a> for each other while preserving <a href=\"/wiki/Grammar\" title=\"Grammar\">grammaticality</a> in all contexts.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Remarks_on_salva_congruitate\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Remarks on <i>salva congruitate</i></span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Timothy_C._Potts\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Timothy C. Potts</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Bob_Hale\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bob Hale</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Remarks_on_salva_congruitate\">Remarks on <i>salva congruitate</i></span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Salva_congruitate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Remarks on salva congruitate\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Timothy_C._Potts\">Timothy C. Potts</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Salva_congruitate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Timothy C. Potts\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Timothy_C._Potts&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Timothy C. Potts (page does not exist)\">Timothy C. Potts</a> describes <i>salva congruitate</i> as a form of replacement in the context of meaning. It is a replacement which preserves <a href=\"/wiki/Semantic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Semantic\">semantic</a> coherence and should be distinguished from a replacement which preserves <a href=\"/wiki/Syntax\" title=\"Syntax\">syntactic</a> coherence but may yield an expression to which no <a href=\"/wiki/Meaning_(philosophy_of_language)\" title=\"Meaning (philosophy of language)\">meaning</a> has been given. This means that supposing an original expression is meaningful, the new expression obtained by the replacement will also be meaningful, though it will not necessarily have the same meaning as the original one, nor, if the expression in question happens to be a <a href=\"/wiki/Proposition\" title=\"Proposition\">proposition</a>, will the replacement necessarily preserve the truth value of the original.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bob_Hale\">Bob Hale</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Salva_congruitate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Bob Hale\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Bob_Hale_(philosopher)\" title=\"Bob Hale (philosopher)\">Bob Hale</a> explains <i>salva congruitate</i>, as applied to singular terms, as <a href=\"/wiki/Noun\" title=\"Noun\">substantival</a> expressions in natural language, which are able to replace singular terms without destructive effect on the <a href=\"/wiki/Syntax\" title=\"Syntax\">grammar</a> of a sentence.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Thus the singular term 'Bob' may be replaced by the definite description 'the first man to swim the English Channel' <i>salva congruitate</i>. Such replacement may shift both meaning and reference, and so, if made in the context of a sentence, may cause a change in truth-value. Thus terms which may be interchanged <i>salva congruitate</i> may not be interchangeable <i>salva veritate</i> (preserving truth). More generally, expressions of any type are interchangeable <i>salva congruitate</i> if and only if they can replace one another preserving grammaticality or well-formedness.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Salva_congruitate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i><a href=\"/wiki/Salva_veritate\" title=\"Salva veritate\">Salva veritate</a></i></li>\n<li><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Reference_principle&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Reference principle (page does not exist)\">Reference principle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Referential_opacity\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Referential opacity\">Referential opacity</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Crispin_Wright\" title=\"Crispin Wright\">Crispin Wright</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Peter_Geach\" title=\"Peter Geach\">Peter Geach</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Salva_congruitate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/W.V.O._Quine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"W.V.O. Quine\">W.V.O. Quine</a>, <i>Philosophy of logic</i></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Dr. Benjamin Schnieder, Canonical Property Designators, P9</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">W.V.O. Quine, Quiddities, P204</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">W.V.O. Quine, Philosophy of Logic, P18</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Timothy C. Potts, <i>Structures and categories for the representation of meaning</i>, p57</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Bob Hale, Singular Terms, P34</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2142\nCached time: 20180914124125\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.084 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.106 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 162/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 335/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 81/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1676/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.015/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 670 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   75.095      1 -total\n 60.73%   45.602      1 Template:Italic_title\n 28.90%   21.704      1 Template:Reflist\n  4.42%    3.321      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:25948756-0!canonical and timestamp 20180914124125 and revision id 577107704\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Concepts_in_logic"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Philosophical_logic"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Philosophy_of_language"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Latin_logical_phrases"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Bob Hale (philosopher)"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Crispin Wright"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Grammar"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Latin"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Logic"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Meaning (philosophy of language)"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Noun"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Peter Geach"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Proposition"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Referential opacity"},{"ns":